What ML does¶

Most frequent applications of ML¶

Problem with classic ML¶

  • Complex data such as Images, Speech, Video & Text
  • Manual feature extraction is complicated
  • When features are large, ML performs bad because of Curse of Dimentionality

Inspiration from 'Brain'¶

Neuron in AI¶

Components of Neuron¶

  • Input : Feature (X) - All inputs will be fed to the neuron
  • Weight (w1, w2..wn) : Slope component of the line : y = w * X + b
  • Activation function : Impose non-linearity (not all relationship between X and y are linear)

Calculation within a Neuron¶

In [35]:
# Loss function 

m = 5 # total samples

y_true = np.array([1, 2, 3, 4, 5]) # actual target labels

y_pred = np.array([1.2, 2.1, 3.09, 4.1, 5.1]) # prediction by model

mse = 1/m * np.sum(np.sqrt((y_true-y_pred)**2)) # loss function = Mean Square Error

# X and y_true are constant
# y_pred is a function of X, w, b
# in other words, tune w, b to adjust y_pred

print(mse)

# Ref to https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mean_squared_error

0.11799999999999984

Evaluation metrics¶

  • Check how good your model is performing
In [34]:
# Metric

m = 5 # total samples

y_true = np.array([1, 2, 1, 2, 1]) # actual target labels

y_pred = np.array([1, 1, 1, 2, 1]) # prediction by model

accuracy = np.where(y_true == y_pred, 1, 0).sum() / m * 100
print(accuracy, '%')

80.0 %

Gradient Descent¶

Analogy 1¶

You will be tuning the weights and bias to take y_pred as close as possible to y_true



Analogy 2¶

Tuning of the parameters should be in the direction to minimize the loss



You may choose the wrong path¶
